M|references|Detailed creation guidance for each lead magnet format.
M|references|- Ebooks & Guides
M|references|- Checklists
M|references|- Cheat Sheets
M|references|- Templates & Spreadsheets
M|references|- Swipe Files
M|references|- Mini-Courses
M|references|- Quizzes & Assessments
M|references|- Webinars & Workshops
M|references|**Best for**: Building authority, deep education, awareness-stage leads
M|references|**Structure**:
M|references|1. Title page with professional design
M|references|2. Table of contents
M|references|3. Introduction — frame the problem, set expectations
M|references|4. 3-7 chapters — one key concept per chapter
M|references|5. Summary — recap key takeaways
M|references|6. CTA — next step toward your product
M|references|**Guidelines**:
M|references|- Ideal length: 10-25 pages (shorter is fine if valuable)
M|references|- Include visuals: charts, diagrams, screenshots
M|references|- Use callout boxes for key stats or quotes
M|references|- End each chapter with a quick takeaway
M|references|- Don't pad — density beats length
M|references|**Tools**: Canva, Google Docs → PDF, Notion export, Designrr, Beacon.by
M|references|**Best for**: Process-oriented tasks, quick wins, implementation help
M|references|**Structure**:
M|references|- Title: "[Number]-Point [Topic] Checklist"
M|references|- Numbered or checkbox items
M|references|- Group into logical sections if 10+ items
M|references|- Brief explanation per item (1-2 sentences)
M|references|**Guidelines**:
M|references|- Keep to 1-2 pages
M|references|- Use actionable language ("Verify X", "Set up Y", "Remove Z")
M|references|- Order by workflow sequence or priority
M|references|- Make it printable — clean layout, generous spacing
M|references|- Include a "done" checkbox for each item
M|references|**What works**: Step-by-step processes, audit criteria, launch checklists, setup guides
M|references|**Best for**: Reference material, shortcuts, quick-lookup information
M|references|**Structure**:
M|references|- One page (two pages max)
M|references|- Organized by category or workflow
M|references|- Dense but scannable
M|references|- Visual hierarchy with headers and grouping
M|references|**Guidelines**:
M|references|- Optimize for quick reference, not reading
M|references|- Use tables, grids, or columns
M|references|- Include formulas, shortcuts, or code snippets
M|references|- Design for printing or saving as desktop reference
M|references|- Bold the most important items
M|references|**What works**: Keyboard shortcuts, formula references, terminology glossaries, dec matrices
M|references|**Best for**: Repeatable processes, planning, tracking
M|references|- Include a "How to Use" tab with instructions
M|references|- Pre-fill with example data
M|references|- Use data validation for dropdown fields
M|references|- Add conditional formatting for visual cues
M|references|- Lock formula cells, leave input cells editable
M|references|- Include a "Make a Copy" link (Google Sheets)
M|references|- Provide a duplicate link
M|references|- Include a getting-started guide
M|references|- Pre-populate with example cnt
M|references|- Use Notion's database features (views, filters, relations)
M|references|- Keep it simple — don't over-engineer
M|references|- Provide in multiple formats (Google Doc, Word, PDF)
M|references|- Include placeholder text with [BRACKETS] for customization
M|references|- Add inline instructions in a different color
M|references|- Make it immediately usable with minimal editing
M|references|**Key principle**: Templates should be usable within 5 minutes of downloading.
M|references|**Best for**: Inspiration, examples, learning from others
M|references|**Structure**:
M|references|- Curated collection of 15-50 examples
M|references|- Organized by category, type, or use case
M|references|- Each example includes:
M|references|- The example itself (screenshot, text, link)
M|references|- Why it works (2-3 bullet annotations)
M|references|- How to adapt it (1-2 sentences)
M|references|**Guidelines**:
M|references|- Quality over quantity — curate ruthlessly
M|references|- Add your analysis, don't just collect
M|references|- Organize for browsing (categories, tags)
M|references|- Update periodically with fresh examples
M|references|- Credit original sources
M|references|**What works**: Email subject lines, landing pages, ad copy, CTAs, onboarding flows, pricing pages
M|references|- 3-5 emails delivered over 5-7 days
M|references|- One lesson per email, one concept per lesson
M|references|- Each email: teach → example → exercise
M|references|- Progressive difficulty (build on previous lessons)
M|references|- Final email: summary + CTA for product or next step
M|references|- 3-5 videos, 5-15 minutes each
M|references|- Host on unlisted YouTube, Loom, or course platform
M|references|- Deliver links via email drip
M|references|- Include worksheets or exercises per lesson
M|references|- More personal — builds stronger connection
M|references|**Cadence**: Every 1-2 days. Don't stretch too thin or compress too tight.
M|references|**Key principle**: Each lesson should deliver standalone value. If someone only watches lesson 2, they should still learn something useful.
M|references|**Best for**: Engagement, segmentation, personalized results
M|references|**Question Design**:
M|references|- 5-10 questions (sweet spot: 7)
M|references|- Multiple choice only — no open-ended
M|references|- Questions should feel insightful, not obvious
M|references|- Progress indicator ("Question 3 of 7")
M|references|**Result Segmentation**:
M|references|- 3-5 result categories
M|references|- Each result: name, description, personalized recommendations
M|references|- Tailor follow-up emails by result type
M|references|- Share-worthy result format ("I got: Growth Stage Marketer!")
M|references|**Implementation**: Gate results behind email capture. The quiz itself is ungated — the personalized results require an email.
M|references|**For building interactive quizzes**: See **free-tool-str** skill for tec implementation guidance.
M|references|- 30-45 minutes teaching + 15 minutes Q&A
M|references|- Structure: Hook → Teach (3 key points) → Demo/example → CTA
M|references|- Promote 1-2 weeks in advance
M|references|- Send 3 reminder emails (confirmation, day before, 1 hour before)
M|references|- Record for replay (extends value)
M|references|- Pre-recorded, available on demand
M|references|- Same structure as live but tighter editing
M|references|- Always-on lead generation
M|references|- Gate with email registration
M|references|- Automated follow-up sequence
M|references|**Follow-up**: Send replay link + summary + CTA within 24 hours. Continue with nurture sequence.
M|references|**Key principle**: Teach something genuinely useful. A webinar that's just a sales pitch will damage trust.